class Solution:
    def countGoodSubstrings(self, s: str) -> int:
        n = len(s)
        count = 0

        for i in range(n - 2):
            if s[i] != s[i+1] and s[i] != s[i+2] and s[i+1] != s[i+2]:
                count += 1

        return count





# Time Complexity 
There are n - 2 substrings.
Each substring has fixed length 3, so checking uniqueness takes constant time.

Time Complexity: O(n) (more precisely, O((n-2) × 3), which simplifies to O(n))

Space Complexity:

Using set: O(1) (the set holds at most 3 characters).
Without set: O(1).
